    "## 2. Importing Libraries\n",
    "\n",
    "### What Each Library Does\n",
    "\n",
    "**pandas** is the foundational library for data manipulation in Python. It introduces the `DataFrame` - a two-dimensional, labelled data structure analogous to a spreadsheet or SQL table. pandas provides tools for reading files (CSV, Excel, JSON), filtering rows, aggregating groups, merging tables, and handling missing values. Every data science project in Python begins here.\n",
    "\n",
    "**NumPy** (Numerical Python) provides the `ndarray` - a fast, memory-efficient multi-dimensional array. While pandas is built *on top of* NumPy, NumPy is used directly when mathematical operations must be applied element-wise across arrays. NumPy is optimised in C, making it orders of magnitude faster than pure Python loops for numerical computation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Difference between pandas and NumPy:** pandas is designed for heterogeneous, labelled, tabular data (mixed types, named columns, index labels). NumPy is designed for homogeneous numerical arrays (all elements same type). Use pandas for data wrangling; use NumPy for mathematical computation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Matplotlib** is Python's base plotting library, offering fine-grained control over every element of a figure. It is verbose but extremely flexible.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Seaborn** is a high-level statistical visualisation library built on Matplotlib. It produces aesthetically refined plots (distribution plots, heatmaps, pair plots, regression plots) with minimal code and integrates naturally with pandas DataFrames.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Scikit-learn (sklearn)** is the standard machine-learning library for Python. It provides a consistent API (`fit`, `predict`, `score`) across dozens of algorithms, as well as preprocessing utilities, model selection tools (cross-validation, grid search), and evaluation metrics.\n",
    "\n",
    "**SciPy** extends NumPy with algorithms for statistics (t-tests, ANOVA, correlation tests), optimisation, signal processing, and linear algebra.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Statsmodels** provides econometrics-style statistical modelling with detailed output - p-values, confidence intervals, and diagnostic tests - that scikit-learn deliberately omits.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if libraries are not imported:** Python raises a `NameError` at runtime when the undefined name is first referenced. The notebook halts and no subsequent code executes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if version conflicts occur:** Incompatible versions can produce silent numerical errors, attribute errors (`AttributeError: module has no attribute '...'`), or deprecation warnings that escalate to exceptions. The safest practice is to pin library versions in a `requirements.txt` file and use a dedicated virtual environment or conda environment per project."
